				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tisseur-de-reves" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2080266); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2080266&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182955" alt="tisseur_de_reves" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2080266)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tisseur-de-reves" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2080266); return false;" >tisseur_de_reves</a></span> <span class="odate time_1426768907 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">19 Mar 2015 12:41</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2253484">
									

<p>After reading this, I can't help but wonder what would happen to matter at a molecular level. For instance, let's say you insert a lump of coal at the small end, and recover it at the other end. You have a lump of coal that's 12 times bigger than the initial one. Now let's say you break a piece in order to analyse it. What happens at molecular level ? Are the molecules 12 times bigger as well, or are there 12 times more molecules ? If that's the case, suppose you rince and repeat the process for N iterations. Would you eventually end up with human sized molecules ?</p>
<p>Another experience : put that lump of coal in a furnace : again, what happens : does the enlarged lump burn 12 times longer than its original &quot;small&quot; counterpart ?</p>
<p>This looks not so much as a funnel as a cornucopia&#8230;</p>

							</div>

								
					
